title: For Sale:  Original 1863 Remington Contract Rifle  .58 Cal
postcontent:
Very RARE ORIGINAL, unfired, Civil War Rifle. A True Collectors piece. This rifle is in EXTREMELY good condition! 
     Model 1863 Rifle manufactured by the Remington Arms Co. in 1863. The Model 1863 Contract Rifle was an improved version of the U.S. Model 1855 Percussion Rifle and was referred to by the Ordnance Department as the "Harpers Ferry Pattern Rifle". The Model 1863 Rifle was the last percussion rifle adopted by the Ordnance Department and is generally considered to be the best designed and highest quality percussion military longarm. The rifle has a heavy 33 inch round barrel with a lug for a sword bayonet on the right side, a dovetail mounted wide base front sight and a folding leaf rear sight graduated 500, 300 and 100 yards. The rifle is fitted with a steel straight shank tulip head ramrod.
     The side lock plate retains almost all its original luster and is patina'd out around the hammer. Manufactured circa 1862 - 1865. The lock is dated 1863 behind the hammer, has the eagle/shield over "U.S." and "REMINGTON'S / ILION, N.Y." in front of the hammer and there is a Sub-Inspectors "L" stamped at the front. The top of the barrel at the breech is dated "1863" followed by "US" over the "V/ P" proofs with the eagle head proof just to the left. The left barrel flat near the breech is stamped STEEL and the inspector's initials H.S.L. The initials are that of of Homer S. Lathe who worked as an armory sub- inspector, inspecting the barrels of Remington M-1863 rifles.  The barrel is blue, casehardened lock and hammer with all brass mountings. Mounted with a full one-piece straight grip walnut stock with a brass carbine style buttplate and patch box. The patch box is stamped with a "L" and the buttplate tang is stamped with "US" and an "J". The left stock flat is marked with crisp cartouches. Script initials "HDJ" (Henry D. Jennings) a Springfield Armory inspector who inspected Remington  M-1863 rifles in a rectangle, and the lower mark has the initials "BH" (Benjamin Hannis) who inspected revolvers as well as Remington rifles, with a rectangular border. The patch box contains an extra percussion nipple. The brass barrel rings are each stamped, one is stamped "P" and the other "U". This Rifle appears unissued and unfired.

Will send more pictures upon request. 
REDACTED

title: For Sale:  WINCHESTER 1886 LIGHTWEIGHT -- .45-70 GOV'T...
postcontent: Here's a classic Winchester that packs a solid punch in a compact package. This is a Winchester Model 1886 Lightweight chambered in .45-70! This handy carbine sized weapon wears a 22" tapered round barrel with iron sights. As was typical of the lightweight variation, it is fitted with a half-magazine and hard rubber shotgun buttplate. Overall condition is very good. The receiver is silver and was probably cleaned at some point in the past with only traces of the original blue finish in the nooks and crannies. The receiver metal is smooth and free of any pitting. The barrel retains about 90% of the original blue finish with some fading in a few spots and some scattered minor handling marks. The forend cap and magazine plug are both worn to silver. The screw heads are sharp, not buggered, but the forend cap screws are not sitting flush and may be cross-threaded. The stocks are in good shape, free of cracks, chips, or repairs. The stocks appear fo have been carefully refinished at some time in the past but were not over-sanded and wood to metal fit is still good.
